  "texts": [
    "Therefore, it makes sense to talk about harmonic maps from a Riemann surface Σ.",
    "A map h: (B 2, c) → (N, g N) is called weakly conformal ifh * g N = νǧ,for some (and hence any) metric ǧ ∈ c and some smooth non-negative function ν: B 2 → R. We emphasise that ν can have zeros; for example, any constant map is weakly conformal, with ν ≡ 0.Example 4.1.",
    "Recall that (after fixing an orientation), a Riemann surface admits a holomorphic atlas.",
    "If dim N = 2, then a map h: Σ → (N 2, g N) is weakly conformal if and only if h is holomorphic or antiholomorphic.Suppose now that G is a real reductive Lie group with maximal compact subgroup K ≤ G. If (g B, ρ, h) solves the twisted harmonic-Einstein equation (4) for the pair (B 2, G/K), then h is necessarily weakly conformal by (20b).",
    "Indeed, Ric(g B) = K(g B)g B, where K(g B) denotes the Gauss curvature."
